{\rtf1\ansi \deff0{\fonttbl{\f8\fswiss Arial;}}\margl1440\margr1440\pgnstart163\sectd\pgnrestart\pgnstarts163\footery1080{\header \pard\plain\qr MYARC ADVANCED BASIC\par }{\footer \pard\plain\qr     VERSION 4.0  DDI SOFTWARE  \chpgn \par }\pard\qj \plain\f8\fs20 POSITION --Subprogram\tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab        POSITION\par \par \par \par \par Format\par CALL POSITION(#sprite-number,numeric-variable1,numeric-variable2[,...])\par \par Cross Reference\par SPRITE\par \par Description\par The POSITION subprogram enables you to ascertain the current position of one or more sprites.\par \par \tab The sprite-number is a numeric-expression whose value specifies the number of the sprite as \par \tab assigned in the SPRITE subprogram.\par \par \tab The current screen position of a sprite is returned as two numeric-variables representing the \par \tab pixelrow and pixelcol, respectively, specifing the position of a screen pixel.\par \par The screen position of the pixel in the upper-left corner of a sprite is considered to be the position of that sprite.\par \par Note that a sprite in motion continues to move during and following the execution of the POSITION subprogram. Remember to allow for this continued motion in your program.\par \par Example\par \par 100 CALL POSITION(#1,Y,X)\par Returns the position of the upper left corner of sprite #1. Also see the third example of the SPRITE subprogram.\par }
